1. Introduction¶

Among the data science community, image classification problems are a huge topic in several sub-fields, where many methods have been developed. One major usage of image classification is for website protection measures by using the computer’s ability to identify whether a user is a robot or not. Many websites prompt users to select a certain type of image to prove whether they are a robot or not by correctly selecting the appropriate image(s). However, with machine learning algorithms, we questioned the integrity of these website protectors and how great of an accuracy are they against humans at passing the test. According to an article on CAPTCHA by the Baymard Institute (2018), humans tend to fail the test around 8-29% of the time. This suggests that humans tend to misclassify images 18.5% of the time on average. As for our classification analysis, we are examining whether a computer model can be more effective at identifying if an image is a non-living or a living object than a human using the CIFAR-10 dataset.

In [3]:
# Load data.

# Note: It was easier to import the data directly as training and test sets.

2. Data Collection¶

The CIFAR-10 image dataset is a widely used dataset for machine learning and image recognition that consists of 10 class images (i.e., airplane, car, bird, cat, deer, dog, frog, horse, ship, and truck) each with 6,000 images per class and 32x32 color pixels. The data was accessed using tensorflow.keras package, where the data was additionally split into training and test datasets among 2 feature matrices and 2 target vectors with 5,000 and 1,000 images, respectively.

# Examine Color Platte Summary 
img = X_train_object[0]
pixels = np.float32(img.reshape(-1, 3))
average = X_train_object[0].mean(axis=0).mean(axis=0)
n_colors = 5
criteria = (cv2.TERM_CRITERIA_EPS + cv2.TERM_CRITERIA_MAX_ITER, 200, .1)
flags = cv2.KMEANS_RANDOM_CENTERS
_, labels, palette = cv2.kmeans(pixels, n_colors, None, criteria, 10, flags)
_, counts = np.unique(labels, return_counts=True)
dominant = palette[np.argmax(counts)]
avg_patch = np.ones(shape=img.shape, dtype=np.uint8)*np.uint8(average)
indices = np.argsort(counts)[::-1]   
freqs = np.cumsum(np.hstack([[0], counts[indices]/float(counts.sum())]))
rows = np.int_(img.shape[0]*freqs)
dom_patch = np.zeros(shape=img.shape, dtype=np.uint8)

for i in range(len(rows) - 1):
    dom_patch[rows[i]:rows[i + 1], :, :] += np.uint8(palette[indices[i]])
    
fig, (ax0, ax1) = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(12,6))
ax0.imshow(avg_patch)
ax0.set_title('Average color')
ax0.axis('off')
ax1.imshow(dom_patch)
ax1.set_title('Dominant colors')
ax1.axis('off')
plt.show(fig)

As a result, the top five most prominent colors used are a medium-dark grey scaling.

4. Data Pre-processing¶

Before performing any model analysis, we had reshaped the dimensions of our images to be a 2D array for both the training and test datasets from 4D to easily couple the information across the dimensions. Without this step, the data wouldn’t be able to process and learn the information on a row-by-row basis.

In [16]:
# reshape dimensions to be 2d array for both the train and test sets
nsamples_train, nx, ny, nrgb = X_train.shape
X_train_2d = X_train.reshape((nsamples_train,nx*ny*nrgb))
nsamples_test, nx, ny, nrgb = X_test.shape
X_test_2d = X_test.reshape((nsamples_test,nx*ny*nrgb))

Next, we split a portion of the training data to create our validation dataset to be used later in validating the test set results in the prevention of overfitting our training data. Resulting in the training set representing 2/3, and the validation and test set each representing 1/6 of the original dataset.

In [17]:
# split training data to validate model testing
X_train, X_valid, y_train, y_valid = train_test_split(X_train_2d, y_train_cl, test_size=0.2, stratify=y_train_cl, random_state=100)

Lastly, despite the pixels showing normality, each feature matrix was normalized so that each image had an average value of 0 and a standard deviation of 1 to ensure that each feature would have equal weight when modeling.

In [18]:
# perform normalization 
scaler = StandardScaler()

X_valid_standard = scaler.transform(X_valid)
X_test_standard = scaler.transform(X_test_2d)

5. Initializing Model¶

As for our model analysis, we used the logistic regression method for our initial model baseline due to its probabilistic nature in predicting an event from a linear combination of predictors or in this case image features. In addition, this method is simple to implement, efficient to train, and easily interpretable in understanding the effects that each predictor or image feature has on the model. However, due to the simplicity of this method, logistic regression tends to overfit when using high-dimensional data and doesn’t support multicollinearity. Thus, we must be cautious since this data had 3,072 observations for each image and that pixels tend to be correlated due to items in images spanning multiple pixels.

6. Model Optimization¶

When optimizing our model, we performed neural networks due to their ability in resembling the inner workings of a human brain by using interconnected nodes or neurons in a layered structure, which is also known as deep learning covered underneath the machine learning process. In addition, neural networks are known to be more efficient, continuous learners, and multitasks. However, they are data-dependent and black-box in nature making it difficult for modifications and the comprehension of what’s going on behind the scenes. Despite the disadvantages, we wanted to see if this form of method could be used to improve the model’s overall accuracy and can out beat an actual human’s accuracy in comparison. As for the model metrics used in designing the model, we began with using one hidden layer with 29 neurons and a ReLU activation function, since it provided the best model accuracy when running these two features. Next, we decided to add a dropout layer since our model was overfitting to the training data with a rate of 36% since it gave the best model accuracy. Then, we decided to add an output layer with a sigmoid activation function since our model is performing a binary classification. Afterward, the model was compiled using a Stochastic Gradient Descent (SGD) optimizer since image classification models tend to optimize better with SGD than the Adam optimizer because it generalizes better despite being slower. In addition, the loss function was set to use a binary cross entropy because as entioned previously, this is a binary classification problem. Lastly, we decided to use a batch size of 200 and 59 epochs since it gave the best model accuracy after experimenting with the two metrics for several other combinations of values.

In [22]:
# set random seed
seed(2023)
tf.random.set_seed(2023)

# design 
model_nn = Sequential()
model_nn.add(Dense(29, activation='relu', input_shape=(X_train_standard.shape[1], )))
model_nn.add(Dropout(rate=.36))
model_nn.add(Dense(1, activation='sigmoid'))
model_nn.summary()
model_nn.compile(optimizer='sgd',
              loss='binary_crossentropy',
              metrics=['accuracy'])

# fit model
history = model_nn.fit(X_train_standard, y_train, epochs=59, batch_size=200, verbose=0,
                    validation_data=(X_valid_standard, y_valid))

7. Compare Model Performances¶

Here we examined the model performances of both methods by first examining their ROC curve plots along with their Area Under the Curve (AUC) values. We used the ROC curve plots and AUC values to compare both model performances visually and numerically, respectively in the figure below. The ROC curve plot measures the model performance by plotting its False Positive Rate (FPR) versus its True Positive Rate (TPR) to determine whether the model can appropriately account for the classification. FPR also known as (1- Specificity) accounts for the rate at which an image was inaccurately classified, in other words when an image was classified as a non-living object when being a living object. TPR also known as Sensitivity or Recall accounts for the rate at which all the relevant image classes within the dataset are determined, in other words when an image was classified as a non-living object when being a non-living object. Ideally, we want the model to perform with a TPR of 1 and an FPR of 0, which is an asymptote sloping along the x and y axes on the upper-left-most corner of a graph. In addition, the AUC value is a metric falling within the range of 0 to 1 used to numerically measure a model’s ROC curve with 1 being the highest possible value indicating perfect model performance.

In [35]:
# Plot 
fpr_lr, tpr_lr, _lr = roc_curve(y_test_cl, probs_lr_test)
fpr_nn, tpr_nn, _nn = roc_curve(y_test_cl, probs_nn_test)

plt.plot(fpr_lr, tpr_lr, label = "Logistic Regression (LR) Model")
plt.plot(fpr_nn, tpr_nn, label = "Neural Network (NN) Model")

plt.title("ROC Curve Model Comparison")
plt.legend(loc="lower right")
plt.xlabel('FPR / (1 - Specificity)')
plt.ylabel('TPR / Recall / Sensitivity')
plt.show()

As a result, we noticed that the neural network model had outperformed the logistic regression model. Based on the ROC curve plot, the neural networks performed way closer at almost capturing all its true positives, while minimizing its false positive rate. Based on the AUC values, the neural network model exceeded the logistic regression model by scoring 0.14 higher with a 0.94 AUC value.

Secondly, we examined the model performances of both methods in terms of accuracy, precision, recall, and f1-score, where we used accuracy as our model metric in determining the better-fitted model. Accuracy is a metric that measures the ability to how close the model can measure its true value. It was used as our metric to be ultimately compared against the performance of a human’s ability in accurately assessing image classification. However, we are aware that accuracy isn’t always the best metric for assessing classification models, especially for imbalanced data. Thus, precision and recall were also used in assessing both models’ performances along with f1-score.

Precision was used to measure the data’s quality by having the ability to determine how well the model can return the correct image in a class. Recall, also known as TPR, was used to measure quantity by having the ability to determine how well the model can find all the relevant image classes within the dataset. F1-score is another form of metric that measures the model's accuracy while checking the balance for precision and recall, where it's often used for uneven class distributions. Since both models produced a f1-score above 0.7 the model is sufficient, where the neural network model is nearly 10% better than the logisitic model.

Lastly, note that we had also tested for model error in both models using root mean square error (RMSE), which was used to measure how accurately the model predicts the response and whether the model results were reliable enough to be used. Since both models fell between the range of 0.2-0.5, both models suggest that they can relatively predict the data accurately, whereas the neural network model with 29.9% model error produced roughly 6.6% less error than the logistic model.

Although the neural network model produced 2.05% fewer misclassifications than the logistic regression model, we noticed that the results for both models show airplane as the most misclassified class, while truck as the least misclassified class. Overall, both models had misclassified the following classes from greatest to least: airplane, autombile, bird, cat, deer, dog, ship, frog, horse, and truck.

Based on our EDA, we can infer that distribution of color relative to target image size has heavy influence on the softwares ability in classifying the images. For example, most of the images for trucks were largely covers in pixel area in comparison to the background unlike airplane. This then makes sense that the model results produce the least misclassifications for the truck imagesin comparison to airplane images. Thus, indicating that the model is falsely training images by these images color palatte background more so than the target images itself. However, we plan to investigate further to conduct whether other possible factors are at play as well.

8. Conclusion, Limitations, and Future Work¶

Conclusion: Our team proposes that the optimization model using neural networks as to be the most effective for image classification. Based on our results, it has the best overall model performance in comparison to the logistic regression. In addition, using the Baymard Institute of 2018 article average statistic, the model performs 6.6% more accurately than a human does on average. Thus, outperforming most humans in accurately assessing image classification.

Future Work: Lastly among both models, we noticed that most misclassified images were airplanes, while the least misclassified images were trucks. Hopefully, with more time and resources, we could better account for these misclassifications moving forward possibly by performing better model fit, imbalanced data analysis, and etc.

Limitatons: Due to the unknown nature of our fit, we presume conducting further investigation in its development would help account for possibility improving the model's accuracy. Based on some articles, this phenomenon could be caused by a number of factors. One being the data between the training and validation must be different in some way. Thus, most suggest to reevaluate the data distribution/ data splitting method, add more data for the validation set, or check the usage of the performance metric being appropriate.
